<map version="1.0.1"><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#90CAF9" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Analysis"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>Material from lectures of Francis Su</p></body></html></richcontent><node POSITION="right" BACKGROUND_COLOR="#9ED0F9" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Counting"><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#ACD7FA" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Function"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A relation where if two members of the co-domain are different, the corresponding members of the domain are different.</p></body></html></richcontent><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Surjective function"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A function is surjective (onto) if its range is the same as the co-domain. That is, a function f from set A to set B is onto if for maps set A onto all of set B.</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Injective function "><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A function f is injective (1-to-1) if two members of the domain being equal implies that there images in the co-domain are equal. That is, x=y =&gt; f(x)=f(y).</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Bijective function"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A function is bijective if it is both surjective and injective (onto and 1-1).</p></body></html></richcontent></node></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#ACD7FA" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Elementary counting"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>Elementary counting involves assigning to a set of n members a set A = Jn = {1,2,...n}</p></body></html></richcontent><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Finite "><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A set A is finite if A can be mapped in one-to-one correspondence with Jn where Jn = {1,2,...,n}.</p></body></html></richcontent></node></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#ACD7FA" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Countable"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A set A is countable if A can have a one-to-one correspondence (a bijection) with the set of natural numbers.</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#ACD7FA" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Uncountable"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>An uncountable set is infinite and not countable.</p></body></html></richcontent></node></node><node POSITION="left" BACKGROUND_COLOR="#9ED0F9" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Sets"><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#ACD7FA" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Power set"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>The power set of a set A is the set of all subsets of A.</p></body></html></richcontent><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Cantour's Theorem"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>(Diagonal Argument) There is no one-to-one correspondence between a set and its power set.</p></body></html></richcontent></node></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#ACD7FA" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Metric space"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A set X is a metric space of there exists a metric d that maps the cross product of X to the real numbers such that for all p and q in X:
1. d(p,q)&gt;=0;
2. d(p,q)=d(q,p); and
3. d(p,q)&lt;=d(q,p).

Note: 1. is non-negativety, 2. is symmetry and 3. is the triangle inequality.</p></body></html></richcontent><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Open ball"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>The open ball (neighbourhood) Nr(x)={y:d(x,y) &lt; r}</p></body></html></richcontent><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Limit point"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A point P in a metric space is a limit point of a set E when every neighbourhood of P contains a point Q in E such that P does not equal Q.</p></body></html></richcontent><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Isolated point"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A point P in a set E is an isolated point if P is not a limit point.</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Interior point"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A point P in a set E is an interior point if there exists a neighbourhood N(P) such that N(P) is a subset of E.</p></body></html></richcontent><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Open set"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A set E is an open set if every point of E is an interior point of E.</p></body></html></richcontent><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Theorem - relationship between open and closed sets"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A set E in a metric space X is open if and only if the complement of E in X is closed.</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Theorem - intersection and union of open and closed sets"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>a. The arbitrary union of open sets is open.
b. The arbitrary intersection of closed sets is closed.
c. A finite intersection of open sets is open.
d. The union of closed sets is closed.</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Theorem - open sets in a metric space within a metric space"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A set E in a metric space Y, which is contained in a metric space X is open if and only if E is the intersection of Y with a set G open in X.</p></body></html></richcontent></node></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Closed set"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A set E is closed if E contains all of its limit points.</p></body></html></richcontent><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Theorem - closed set"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A set E is closed if and only if E = the closure of E.</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Theorem - contained closure"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>If set E is contained  in a closed set F, the closure of E is contained in F.</p></body></html></richcontent></node></node></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Theorem - points in a neighbourhood of a limit point"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>Every neighbourhood of a limit point P in a set E has infinitely many points in E.</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Closure"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>The closure of a set E is the union of E and the limit points of E.</p></body></html></richcontent><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Theorem - closure"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>The closure of a set A is a closed set.</p></body></html></richcontent></node></node></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Lemma - neighbourhoods"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>Neighbourhoods are open.</p></body></html></richcontent></node></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Closed ball"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>The closed ball Nr(x)={y:d(x,y) &lt;= r}</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Dense"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A set E in a metric space X is dense if every point of X is a limit point of E or is in E
or X is the closure of E
or every open set of X contains a point of E.</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Bounded set"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A set K in metric space X is bounded if K is contained in Nr(x) for some x in X.</p></body></html></richcontent></node></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#ACD7FA" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Lemma - intersections and unions of sets"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>The complement of a union of sets is equal to the intersection of the complements of those sets.</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#ACD7FA" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Open cover"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>An open cover of set E in a metric space X is a collection of open sets whose  union contains E.
</p></body></html></richcontent><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Subcover"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A subcover is a sub-collection of sets within a cover that still covers a set.</p></body></html></richcontent><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Compact set"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A set K is compact if every open cover of  K contains a finite subcover.</p></body></html></richcontent><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Theorem - finite sets"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>Finite sets are compact.</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Theorem - compact set bounded"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A compact set is bounded.</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Theorem - compactness in contained metric space"><richcontent TYPE="NOTE"><html><head /><body><p>A set K in a metric space Y, which is contained in a metric space X is compact in Y if and only if K is compact in X.</p></body></html></richcontent></node><node BACKGROUND_COLOR="#BBDEFB" COLOR="#000000" TEXT="Theorem - compact sets are closed" /></node></node></node></node></node></map>